---
import Base from "../../layouts/Base.astro";
import TracePlayer from "../../islands/TracePlayer.svelte";
import LessonNav from "../../components/LessonNav.astro";
import buggy from "../../../derived/roundoff/buggy.trace.json";
import procedural from "../../../derived/roundoff/procedural.trace.json";

// Buggy first: watch == fail on 0.1 + 0.2, then watch a tolerance check do it right.
const registers = [buggy, procedural];
---

<Base
  title="Roundoff — GlassBox"
  description="Watch 0.1 + 0.2 come out as 0.30000000000000004 — and why comparing floats with == is a trap."
>
  <LessonNav slug="roundoff" position="top" />

  <h1>Roundoff</h1>
  <p class="lede">
    Decimals like <code>0.1</code> have no exact representation in binary, the same way <code>1/3</code> has no exact decimal. So <code>0.1 + 0.2</code> lands a hair off <code>0.3</code>, and asking <code>== 0.3</code> returns <code>False</code>. This is roundoff — a representation error — and it is a different beast from <a href="../overflow/">overflow</a>, which is a fixed-width wrap.
  </p>

  <TracePlayer registers={registers} client:visible />

  <section class="explain card">
    <h2>What you are looking at</h2>
    <p>
      Both versions compute <code>total = 0.1 + 0.2</code>, and both show the same surprising value:
      <code>0.30000000000000004</code>. The difference is how they <em>compare</em> it.
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>
        <strong>Buggy</strong> — asks <code>total == 0.3</code>. The tiny tail means total is not exactly <code>0.3</code>, so the answer is <code>False</code> and the program decides they are "off by a hair". Comparing floats with <code>==</code> is the classic mistake.
      </li>
      <li>
        <strong>Procedural</strong> — asks whether <code>total</code> is <em>close</em> to <code>0.3</code>
        (<code>abs(total - 0.3) &lt; 0.0001</code>). It is, so the answer is <code>True</code>. The fix for
        float comparison: never <code>==</code>, always a tolerance.
      </li>
    </ul>
    <p class="fineprint">
      Every state you see came from running the program under CPython's tracer at build time — see <a href="../../verification/">how GlassBox stays honest</a>.
    </p>
  </section>
  <LessonNav slug="roundoff" position="bottom" />
</Base>

<style>
  .explain { margin-top: 1.4rem; }
  .explain ul { margin: 0.6rem 0; padding-left: 1.1rem; }
  .explain li { margin: 0.5rem 0; }
  .fineprint { color: var(--ink-faint); font-size: 0.9rem; margin-bottom: 0; }
</style>
